Notebook one. SQL foundations and the relational model.

This is the opening notebook in the SQL series. By the end of it you should understand what SQL actually is, the shape of the relational model that sits underneath it, how the database enforces correctness through keys and constraints, what normalization is really asking you to do, why writing SQL feels different from writing imperative code, and the rough landscape of dialects you will run into in the wild. We will also create our first tables inside an embedded DuckDB engine so the rest of the series has something concrete to work against.

Let us start with what SQL is. SQL stands for structured query language. It is a declarative language for talking to relational databases. The word declarative is the important one. You describe the result you want, and the engine figures out how to produce it. You do not write loops. You do not pick which index to use. You write a question, and the database planner picks the strategy.

If you are coming from the java virtual machine world, the closest mental model is Java Streams. When you write a stream pipeline with filter and map and collect, you are saying what you want, not how to do it. SQL pushes that same idea much further. The engine can reorder operations, pick join algorithms, decide whether to use an index, and split the work across many cores, all from the same query text.

SQL was born at I-B-M in the nineteen seventies. It was standardized as ansi SQL, and somehow, fifty years later, it still runs the data world. Online transactional databases, data warehouses, embedded engines, business intelligence tools, even modern stream processors. They all speak some flavor of SQL.

Now the relational model. Three words do almost all the work here. A relation is a table. A tuple is a row. An attribute is a column. A table has a fixed set of typed columns. Every row is one fact, stated in those columns. The key thing to internalize is that row order is not guaranteed. The engine is free to give you rows back in whatever order is convenient for it. If you want a specific order in your result, you ask for it explicitly with order by.

Picture a customers table with three columns. Customer id, name, and email. Three rows: Alice, Bob, and Carol. That is the shape we will use throughout this notebook. Alice and Bob have emails. Carol does not, so her email column holds null. We will come back to null shortly because it behaves in a surprising way.

To make this concrete we will use DuckDB. DuckDB is an embedded analytical database. There is no server to install and no daemon to run. It is just a file on disk and a library you load. In a Python notebook we load the SQL magic with percent load extension SQL, and then connect with percent SQL duck-d-b colon slash slash slash learn dot d-b. After that any cell that starts with double percent SQL runs as a query, and the results render directly underneath.

We create the customers table with create table customers. Customer id is an integer and it is the primary key. Name is a varchar and not null. Email is a varchar and unique. Signup date is a date and also not null. Then we insert three rows for Alice, Bob, and Carol. Select star from customers gives us the table back.

That brings us to keys and constraints. Constraints are how the database refuses to store invalid data. The engine enforces them on every insert and every update, which means bad data never lands in the first place. This is a very different posture from validating in application code where bad data can sneak in through any path that bypasses the validator.

There are five constraints to know. The primary key uniquely identifies a row. It is effectively not null plus unique, and it doubles as the table's identity column. A foreign key is a column that must match a primary key in another table. If you try to insert a row whose foreign key does not resolve, the engine refuses. If you try to delete a parent row that would orphan children, the engine refuses. Unique means no two rows share that value. Not null means a value is required. Check is the catch-all: any boolean condition you can express, the engine will enforce per row.

Foreign keys are how the relational model glues independent facts together. We create an orders table where each order has an order id as primary key, a customer id that references customers customer id, an amount with a check that the amount is greater than zero, and an order date. Three orders go in, two for Alice and one for Bob. When we try to insert a fourth order with customer id ninety nine, the engine rejects it with a foreign key violation, because customer ninety nine does not exist. That is the database protecting your data model.

Section four is normalization. Normalization is the rulebook for how to split data into tables. There are higher forms in the textbooks, but in practice three of them cover almost everything you will hit. First normal form says every cell holds one atomic value. No comma separated lists. No j-son blobs standing in for what should really be rows. Second normal form says non-key columns depend on the whole primary key, and it only matters when your key is composite. Third normal form says non-key columns depend on nothing but the primary key. No transitive dependencies like an order pointing at a customer id which in turn determines the customer address.

The intuition behind all three is the same. Things that vary independently belong in their own table, connected by foreign keys. A customer's address that changes over time should not force you to update every single order that customer ever placed. Split it out, link it with a foreign key, and now the address can move without dragging the order history with it.

Section five. Declarative thinking. This is the hardest mental shift if you come from imperative code. You do not write loops. You do not pick the index. You write a question. Give me each customer's total spend, highest first. The engine then plans the work. Which index to scan. Which join algorithm to pick. Whether to parallelize across cores. That plan can change tomorrow as the data grows, or as you add a new index, without you rewriting the query. The query stays the same; the strategy adapts.

The rule of thumb is, trust the planner first. Only override it when the explain plan shows the planner is making a wrong choice. We will meet explain properly in notebook eight, when we talk about query planning and indexes.

Section six is a quick tour of the dialect landscape. Most everyday SQL is portable across engines. The places dialects diverge are window function syntax, date and time functions, j-son and array handling, and the merge or upsert syntax. PostgreSQL is open source and the closest thing to a reference dialect. MySQL and MariaDB are the web stack default, historically with looser semantics, though MySQL eight and onward has tightened a lot. SQL Server, sometimes called T-SQL, is Microsoft's enterprise dialect, and famously uses top instead of limit. SQLite is the tiny embedded engine that lives inside every phone and every browser. DuckDB is the embedded analytical engine we are using throughout this series. And then the cloud warehouses: Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift, each with their own quirks, notably window function extensions like qualify. Throughout this series we will write standard ansi SQL and call out dialect specific syntax explicitly whenever it comes up.

Section seven. Pitfalls to carry forward into every notebook that follows. Five of them. First, forgetting where on an update or a delete touches every row in the table. Always run the same filter as a select first, see what you would change, and only then commit to the change. Second, comparing to null with the equals sign. Null is not equal to anything, including itself. The expression x equals null is always unknown, which the engine treats as false. Use x is null or x is not null instead. Third, select star in production code. When the underlying columns change, your downstream code breaks silently. Name the columns you actually need. Fourth, a table with no primary key. Without one, the engine cannot enforce row identity, and many tools, from object relational mappers to replication systems to business intelligence tools, will misbehave. Fifth, trusting row order without an order by clause. The engine is free to return rows in any order it likes. The order you see today is not the order you are guaranteed tomorrow.

That closes notebook one. Next up is notebook two, querying with select, where we use these same customers and orders tables to learn the read path properly.
